{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"637267d8-0eaf-4cc2-86b9-92283cb0f80b","content":"`SafeAreaEdges` isn't a standard .NET MAUI property — that's likely your issue. Here's what you actually need:\n\n**iOS** — use the platform-specific `UseSafeArea`:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\">\n    <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\n**Android** — enable edge-to-edge in `MainActivity.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n    AndroidX.Core.View.WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false);\n}\n```\n\n> **Note:** On Android 15+ (API 35), edge-to-edge is enforced by default, but MAUI's default layouts may still apply window inset padding. The `SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(false)` call tells the framework *you'll* handle insets — then simply don't apply them to your image.\n\n**Also check** that your `Image` and any parent layout have `Padding=\"0\"` and `Margin=\"0\"` — `Grid`, `VerticalStackLayout`, etc. can introduce spacing.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4b777b0e-546b-4061-8c1f-ba893bf42d5c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making content go edge-to-edge in a .NET MAUI app, going behind the status bar and navigation bar. They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but still see padding.\n\nThis is a common .NET MAUI question. Let me think about what's needed:\n\nIn .NET MAUI, to achieve true edge-to-edge content that goes behind system bars, you need to:\n\n1. **Set `IgnoreSafeArea`** on the view itself (the `Image` control), not just on the page. `SafeAreaEdges` on `ContentPage` controls which edges the page respects for safe area insets, but individual views may still respect safe area by default.\n\n\n2. On **Android**, edge-to-edge isn't automatic in .NET 8+, so you'll need to configure the status bar and navigation bar to be translucent or use platform-specific APIs to disable system window fitting.\n3. On **iOS**, using `SafeAreaEdges` or `IgnoreSafeArea` on the page or view should handle it, though the approach differs slightly from Android.\n\nActually, I need to be more precise here. `IgnoreSafeArea` isn't a standard MAUI property I'm confident about. For iOS specifically, the platform-specific approach is `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` to let content extend behind safe areas. On Android, you're configuring edge-to-edge through platform code with `WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(window, false)` or the newer edge-to-edge API. I'm wondering if there are newer APIs available in .NET 9 or 10 that might simplify this. For iOS, I need to use the platform-specific `UseSafeArea` property set to false on the page. On Android, the approach involves enabling edge-to-edge mode through the platform code, likely using `WindowCompat.SetDecor` or similar APIs. The `SafeAreaEdges` property the user mentioned doesn't appear to be a standard MAUI property, so I should clarify the correct approach for both platforms.\n\nI should also note that in newer versions of .NET and Android, edge-to-edge rendering is often the default, but the system still applies insets through the layout—the real trick is ensuring those insets don't affect the image itself. I'll focus on the key steps: disabling safe area on iOS, enabling edge-to-edge on Android, setting the image aspect to fill, and removing any margins or padding that might interfere.","outputTokens":1394,"requestId":"943B:353499:13910BF:15E9192:6A066E7C"},"id":"91e9960c-b70d-46ac-b9a6-f07c45af6558","timestamp":"2026-05-15T00:53:43.382Z","parentId":"3a925d91-9583-4f93-8c7a-c530776857d7"}
